aid on Thursday.</p><p>But only £30m of the money, for repairs and maintenance, will be available this year, with the rest in the following year. No extra money for building new flood defences in future was announced.</p><p>The communities secretary told MPs the weather had been \"savage\" and paid tribute to \"the work of councils, the staff on the ground from the Environment Agency and the emergency services - they have literally gone through hell and high water.\"</p><p>Pickles, who noted existing flood defences had protected 1.2m homes, added: \"It is evident that flood defences had taken a real pounding. There will be an urgent review of how to restore and maintain flood defences in target condition.\" He said a long-term strategy for flood protection running to 2021 would be delivered by the autumn.</p><p>Pickles criticised the Environment Agency chairman, Lord Smith, who had suggested there was a choice between protecting \"<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/environment/2014/feb/03/flood-protection-town-country-environment-agency-warns\" title=\"\">front rooms or farmland</a>\", with Pickles saying lessons would be learned from recent problems including \"the local accountability of quangos\".</p><p>Shadow environment secretary, Maria Eagle, said: \"The government was caught out by the floods and it took far too long for ministers to realised the seriousness of the situation. There have been 21 meeting of [emergency committee] Cobra but it is far from clear what all the talk has achieved.\" She also accused ministers of \"fiddling the figures\" over flood defence spending, after Pickles used a different baseline from that of Cameron on Wednesday. Annual flood defence spending <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/environment/2014/jan/06/david-cameron-claim-flood-spending\" title=\"\">fell by 15% under the coalition</a>.</p><p>Pickles, who was standing in for the environment secretary, Owen Paterson, who is having emergency eye surgery, also confirmed changes to the <a href=\"https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/bellwin-scheme-2013-to-2014-guidance\" title=\"\">Bellwin scheme</a>, through which councils can claim funding for damage repairs. They will be able to claim 100% of losses over a threshold, not 85%, and will have to the end of March to claim.</p><p>On the severing of the mainline London-Penzance railway after a <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/video/2014/feb/05/uk-storms-dawlish-seawall-collapses-railway-battered-extreme-weather-video\" title=\"\">sea wall collapsed at Dawlish</a>, Pickles said: \"We are not in a position to know how long it will take [to repair].\"</p><p>Earlier, the transport secretary, Patrick McLoughlin, told MPs he has asked for a report on improving the resilience of the rail network in the south-west: \"The immediate priority is to assess the damage and develop a plan for getting the line back into service as soon as possible,\" he said. \"But I am acutely conscious of the need to develop a long-term solution to the resilience of the railway network in the south-west, and I have asked for a report on the options for addressing this problems.\"</p><p>John Disney, a senior lecturer at Nottingham business school, said he expected the line to remain closed until Easter (20 April). \"It was entirely predictable that the sea was going to win the 'battle of Dawlish' sweeping away Brunel's coastline railway and it is amazing that it has lasted until 2014, due mainly to Network Rail's excellent infrastructure maintenance regime,\" he said. \"The sea wall has now succumbed, however, and the railway is left suspended in mid-air and will take several weeks to repair; I'd be surprised if it was fully reopened before Easter.\"</p><p>There will be no respite from the extreme weather, with the Met Office warning that a fresh wave of heavy rain is hitting southern England and Wales on Thursday morning. They said up to 1.6 inches (40mm) of rain is being predicted to fall on the south coast, where many areas are already drenched from recent storms and floods.</p><p>Upland areas including Salisbury Plain, the South Downs and North Downs are set to be the worst affected by the downpours, and the Met Office has issued an amber warning for the area, urging locals to \"be prepared\". Winds of up to 40mph are set to batter the south coast, potentially bringing dangerously high waves and wreaking fresh damage to these storm-hit areas.</p><p>Another weather system developing off the Atlantic will sweep into Britain bringing up to 1.2 inches (30mm) of rain over Friday night and into Saturday. Severe galeforce winds of up to 80mph are expected to hit southern Britain which could topple trees and cause more damage to the beleaguered region.</p>","headline":"Emergency funding to repair damaged UK flood defences raised to £130m","trailText":"<p>Eric Pickles announces increase from £100m but just £30m will be available this year and will not cover new flood defences</p>","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"theguardian.com","showInRelatedContent":"true","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/3mg9n","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Environment/Pix/pictures/2014/2/6/1391690373262/Extreme-Weather--Floods-i-004.jpg","secureThumbnail":"https://static-secure.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Environment/Pix/pictures/2014/2/6/1391690373262/Extreme-Weather--Floods-i-004.jpg","wordcount":"714","commentable":"true","internalContentCode":"429063861","allowUgc":"false","internalOctopusCode":"8652583","isPremoderated":"false","byline":"Damian Carrington and Matthew Weaver","newspaperEditionDate":"2014-02-07T00:00:00Z","internalPageCode":"2039279","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-02-09T13:02:00Z"},"rights":{"syndicatable":false,"subscriptionDatabases":false},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/environment/2014/feb/06/emergency-funding-uk-flood-defences-storms-weather","apiUrl":"http://internal.content.guardianapis.com/environment/2014/fe