\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Statement on winter <a href=\"https://twitter.com/search?q=%23floods&amp;src=hash\">#floods</a> by <a href=\"https://twitter.com/CommunitiesUK\">@communitiesuk</a> Secretary <a href=\"https://twitter.com/EricPickles\">@EricPickles</a> expected after 11.15am. Watch live online <a href=\"http://t.co/CbJypNm1nV\">http://t.co/CbJypNm1nV</a></p>&mdash; House of Commons (@HouseofCommons) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/HouseofCommons/statuses/431353687055687680\">February 6, 2014</a></blockquote> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-52f368a4e4b0019d0eaa7f03\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-02-06T10:52:50.579Z\">10.52am <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Thirteen people have been rescued from flood stricken vehicles in Devon and Somerset, according to the latest figures local fire and rescue service. <br></p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/DSFireUpdates/statuses/431375788298878976\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Latest statistics show that 13 people were rescued from vehicles in <a href=\"https://twitter.com/search?q=%23floodwater&amp;src=hash\">#floodwater</a> in the last 24 hours. <a href=\"http://t.co/iSsc34dki7\">http://t.co/iSsc34dki7</a> via <a href=\"https://twitter.com/ShareThis\">@sharethis</a></p>&mdash; Devon&amp;Somerset Fire (@DSFireUpdates) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/DSFireUpdates/statuses/431375788298878976\">February 6, 2014</a></blockquote> </figure> <p>The AA said drivers were failing to heed flood warnings. Responding to an earlier update from Devon and Somerset Fire and Rescue, it tweeted: <br></p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/AASORT/statuses/431355591936999424\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Sad that the message isn&#39;t getting thru!&#10;RT <a href=\"https://twitter.com/DSFireUpdates\">@DSFireUpdates</a>: 4 people rescued from vehicles in <a href=\"https://twitter.com/search?q=%23floodwater&amp;src=hash\">#floodwater</a> last night <a href=\"http://t.co/8cL8vRELcy\">http://t.co/8cL8vRELcy</a></p>&mdash; AA SORT (@AASORT) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/AASORT/statuses/431355591936999424\">February 6, 2014</a></blockquote> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-52f365d4e4b0d5e31a93fed0\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-02-06T10:41:53.510Z\">10.41am <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>A railway infrastructure expert and former adviser to the Department of Transport, was warned that the south-west line is unlikely to be repaired before Easter.</p><p>Dr John Disney, a senior lecturer at  Nottingham Business School, said he was surprised that the coastal line had lasted this long.</p><p>In an email he said: <br></p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>It was entirely predictable that the sea was going to win the ‘Battle of Dawlish’ sweeping away Brunel’s coastline railway and it is amazing that it has lasted until 2014, due mainly to Network Rail’s excellent infrastructure maintenance regime.</p><p>The sea wall has now succumbed, however, and the railway is left suspended in mid-air and will take several weeks to repair; I’d be surprised if it was fully reopened before Easter especially as the jet stream is expected to continue powering storms towards the UK – and south-west England in particular – throughout February.</p><p>In the short term arrangements will need to be made to bridge the gap between  Exeter and Plymouth (about 50 miles along the A38) with frequent fast high-quality coach services. Consideration should also be given to reducing fares to reflect the use of road transport.</p><p>It will be impossible to operate the Penzance to London sleeper services and this is an opportunity for an entrepreneurial airline to take advantage of the rail closure by launching a new service. Such services would be much welcomed by the business community in West Devon and Cornwall who otherwise face every business trip to London becoming a two-day endurance test.</p><p>Long-term, serious consideration must now be given to reopening an alternative inland railway line through Devon. There has been little Westminster support for this, but the tide may now be turning. It would be feasible to electrify an inland route so this could link with the Great Western electrification plans and enable through electric trains to operate from London to Plymouth.\"</p></blockquote> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-52f35f82e4b0019d0eaa7ef5\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-02-06T10:20:02.072Z\">10.20am <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Transport secretary Patrick McLoughlin has confirmed that he asked for a report on improving the resilience of the rail network in the south-west after Wednesday's battering.</p><p>Speaking in the Commons he said: <br></p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>An urgent priority is the railway at Dawlish. Colleagues will have seen the images of the devastating impact that the weather has had on the railway there. I met with members of all parties from Devon and Cornwall yesterday evening alongside Network Rail. The immediate priority is to assess the damage and develop a plan for getting the line back into service as soon as possible. But I am acutely conscious of the need to develop a long term solution to the resilience of the railway network in the south-west, and I have asked for a report on the options for addressing this problems. <br></p></blockquote> <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-badbf302-c1e8-4ad9-aa15-9a1dc6f7b862\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/2/6/1391681949624/d9729a13-ed16-4101-9d76-6f742bfdf048-460x276.jpeg\" alt=\"Transport Secretary Patrick McLoughlin arrives at a Cobra meeting at the Cabinet Office in London.\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>Transport Secretary Patrick McLoughlin arrives at a Cobra meeting at the Cabinet Office in London. Photograph: Stefan Rousseau/PA</figcaption> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-52f35ebbe4b0d5e31a93fec7\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-02-06T10:08:38.893Z\">10.08am <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>The AA has warned drivers in the south of England and Wales to expect delays due to flooding. <br></p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/AASORT/statuses/431353630202277888\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Heavy rain expected to last all day &amp; into Fri. Rain for all areas of England/Wales, the South will be worst hit. Expect travel disruption!</p>&mdash; AA SORT (@AASORT) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/AASORT/statuses/431353630202277888\">February 6, 2014</a></blockquote> </figure> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/AASORT/statuses/431310036501938177\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Flooding situation is very serious and large rainfall volumes forecast will only make matters worse. Be <a href=\"https://twitter.com/search?q=%23FloodAware&amp;src=hash\">#FloodAware</a> &#10;&#10;<a href=\"http://t.co/ojqTOcU1Ys\">http://t.co/ojqTOcU1Ys</a></p>&mdash; AA SORT (@AASORT) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/AASORT/statuses/431310036501938177\">February 6, 2014</a></blockquote> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-52f35b09e4b0530e249db082\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-02-06T09:56:05.015Z\">9.56am <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Police in Somerset have played down fears of looting in the flood-stricken Somerset Levels. <br></p><p>Sue Sayer, in the village of Moorland, was quoted by the <a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-26061795\">BBC as saying</a>: \"They're advising, if you can, go. But there's an awful lot of people that are not because the risk then of looting if people see empty houses.</p><p>\"There has already been looting in some properties, not directly in the centre of the village, but on the outskirts there's already been looting which is despicable.\"</p><p>Steven Morris said the police had only had three reports of theft in the area. <br></p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/stevenmorris20/statuses/431361724550094849\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Police in Somerset strongly playing down the idea that there is widespread looting on the Levels - just 3 reports of theft in recent days.</p>&mdash; steven morris  (@stevenmorris20) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/stevenmorris20/statuses/431361724550094849\">February 6, 2014</a></blockquote> </figure> <p>The force also defended its decision to warn people by megaphone from a helicopter to evacuate their homes, Steve writes.<br></p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/stevenmorris20/statuses/431361430307082242\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Avon &amp; Somerset police defending itself against the suggestion they over-reacted by putting up helicopter to warn people about flooding...</p>&mdash; steven morris  (@stevenmorris20) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/stevenmorris20/statuses/431361430307082242\">February 6, 2014</a></blockquote> </figure> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/stevenmorris20/statuses/431361517636710401\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>The force says it was struggling to get in touch with some people in very isolated pockets.</p>&mdash; steven morris  (@stevenmorris20) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/stevenmorris20/statuses/431361517636710401\">February 6, 2014</a></blockquote> </figure> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2014-02-06T09:58:24.837Z\">at 9.58am GMT</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-52f35924e4b0530e249db080\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-02-06T09:48:55.958Z\">9.48am <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Transport secretary Patrick McLoughlin says the government will be working with Network Rail to get the main line to the south west \"restored\" as quickly as possible. <br></p><p>Appearing in the Commons for Transport questions, he said the government would also be conducting a \"rigorous review on some of the other alternatives which may be available\". <br></p><p>McLoughlin said damage to the line was an \"appalling situation\". <br></p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-52f358bee4b0ab978b0f9782\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-02-06T09:41:51.782Z\">9.41am <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Meteo Group confirms the grim foreceast for the weekend.<br></p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/WeatherCast_UK/statuses/431361652592619520\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>More heavy rain and strong winds over the weekend - <a href=\"http://t.co/adQyVudvmi\">http://t.co/adQyVudvmi</a> Average Feb rainfall totals available too <a href=\"http://t.co/OoB0skCbrS\">pic.twitter.com/OoB0skCbrS</a></p>&mdash; MeteoGroup UK (@WeatherCast_UK) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/WeatherCast_UK/statuses/431361652592619520\">February 6, 2014</a></blockquote> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-52f3556ae4b0530e249db07b\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-02-06T09:33:12.606Z\">9.33am <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Anne Marie Morris, the Conservative MP whose Newton Abbot constituency covers Dawlish, said rerouting the damaged line would be too expensive and take too long. <br></p><p>Speaking to BBC News, she said: \"The previous government looked at that, and when they added it up it was clear that that was simply unaffordable.\" <br></p><p>Interviewed alongside the damaged line, she said an alternative route could never replace \"this crucial artery along the coast. It is vital for our tourist industry. It is vital for our communities. And it is absolutely doable to keep this line up and running. And it is much more affordable to do that now, rather than a new railway.\" <br></p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/AMMorrisMP/statuses/431359279015022592\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Interviewed on <a href=\"https://twitter.com/search?q=%23Dawlish&amp;src=hash\">#Dawlish</a> sea front by Ben Brown from BBC News about the help we need to protect our coastal railway <a href=\"http://t.co/RM4wkSORkU\">pic.twitter.com/RM4wkSORkU</a></p>&mdash; Anne Marie Morris MP (@AMMorrisMP) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/AMMorrisMP/statuses/431359279015022592\">February 6, 2014</a></blockquote> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-52f35291e4b0530e249db07a\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-02-06T09:26:31.766Z\">9.26am <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Shadow environment secretary Maria Eagle has attacked the government's response to the flooding crisis as \"delayed and confused\".</p><p>Speaking on BBC News she said the £100m funding package announced by the prime minister would only make up for a year's worth of cuts to the budget for flood defences. <br></p><p>\"What we see today is the prime minister accepting that they took too much money out of the flood protection budget and they are starting to put a bit back,\" she said. </p><p>Eagle said it was \"optimistic\" for Network Rail to claim it repair the main south-west railway line within six weeks. <br></p><p>She said: \"There [are] 1.2 million people west of Dawlish who are now effectively cut off and don't have a rail service, and that has big implications if it isn't fixed. Network Rail, the Environment Agency [and] lot of local agencies need to get their act together fast.\" </p><p>As well as a statement from communities secretary Eric Pickles on the floods, the transport secretary Patrick McLoughlin is due also due to appear in the Commons and is sure to be asked about the south-west mainline. <br></p><p>Another meeting of Cobra, the government's emergency planning committee, will be held this afternoon. <br></p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-52f34d43e4b0ab978b0f9776\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-02-06T08:57:26.809Z\">8.57am <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Communities secretary Eric Pickles is due to make a statement to the Commons this morning to update MPs on the latest on the flooding crisis. He is standing in for the environment secretary, Owen Paterson, who is due have an operation for a detached retina. <br></p><p>The statement is expected between 10.30am and 11am. <br></p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/HouseofCommons/statuses/431347833338228738\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>There will be a statement in the Commons today by Communities Secretary Eric Pickles on the winter <a href=\"https://twitter.com/search?q=%23floods&amp;src=hash\">#floods</a>. More details to follow.</p>&mdash; House of Commons (@HouseofCommons) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/HouseofCommons/statuses/431347833338228738\">February 6, 2014</a></blockquote> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-52f3495be4b0ab978b0f9771\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-02-06T08:51:18.575Z\">8.51am <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Fourteen people, a dog and a budgie were rescued by fire crews in Devon and Somerset overnight according to the local fire service. <br></p><p><a href=\"http://www.dsfire.gov.uk/News/Newsdesk/IncidentDetail.cfm?IncidentID=27913&amp;siteCategoryId=3&amp;T1ID=26&amp;T2ID=41\">Devon and Somerset Fire and Rescue have produced a list of incidents </a>overnight. It included this recorded 3.55am: </p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>﻿The specialist water rescue team from Bridgwater attended a property in Moorland, North Petherton to assist in the evacuation of three adults, a dog and a budgie as the property was flooded.</p></blockquote><p>Two men in Thornfalcon were  also rescued from the bonnet of their car which was stranded in flood water. <br></p><p>\"Ambulance treated the men for the effects of cold,\" a spokesman said. </p><p>Another man was rescued from the roof of his van near Exeter. <br></p><br> <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-466b0f56-ea9e-4ac0-897a-9be029d51599\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/2/6/1391676659322/f02186de-7717-4187-8305-6bc8ea36abae-460x276.jpeg\" alt=\"Volunteers Verity Trevor-Morgan and Marsha Casely make cups of tea at a rest centre that has been set up at North Petherton bowling club for potential victims of flooding in Devon.\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>Volunteers Verity Trevor-Morgan and Marsha Casely make cups of tea at a rest centre that has been set up at North Petherton bowling club for potential victims of flooding in Devon. Photograph: Matt Cardy/Getty Images</figcaption> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-52f345b9e4b0530e249db069\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-02-06T08:33:03.769Z\">8.33am <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Network Rail has warned that it will take \"some weeks\" to repair the main line to Conwall after the track was left dangling over the sea at Dawlish after damage from Wednesday's high tide.</p><p> Interviewed on BBC Radio's Today programme Robin Gisby, managing director of network operations, also said it was \"worth looking\" at rerouting the line inland.</p><p>\"We've got to look at the resilience of all transport links into Devon and Cornwall,\" he said. Gisby added: \"It feels like we're having one-in-a-hundred year events every week at the moment.\"</p><p>Chris Pomfret, chair of the Cornwall and Isles of Scilly Local Enterprise Partnership, told the programme that patching up the railway was urgent but not the solution. <br></p><p>\"The solution is to take a proper strategic look at the transport links to Cornwall. The government needs to makes some decisions and get on with it,\" he said. <br></p><p>Pomfret agreed that part of Cornwall's charm was that it was relatively isolated from the rest of England, but he added: \"That doesn't mean we have to make do with 19th century services.\"</p> <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-44f13cd2-301e-4540-8252-4c822275a14f\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/2/6/1391675550672/414cd939-644b-426d-9649-fea496c34e94-460x276.jpeg\" alt=\"Railway workers inspect the main Exeter to Plymouth  railway line that has been closed due to parts of it being washed away by the sea at Dawlish.\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>Railway workers inspect the main Exeter to Plymouth  railway line that has been closed due to parts of it being washed away by the sea at Dawlish. Photograph: Matt Cardy/Getty Images</figcaption> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-52f33ee9e4b0ab978b0f9763\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-02-06T07:57:40.259Z\">7.57am <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>The BBC's Sophie Pierce notes the contrast in Dawlish today where the sea is relative quiet after Wednesday's chaotic scenes. </p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/sophiepierce/statuses/431332937750306817\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>What a contrast - sea flat in Dawlish this morning cf gargantuan waves of yesterday. More <a href=\"https://twitter.com/BBCDevon\">@BBCDevon</a> <a href=\"https://twitter.com/radiowoodley\">@radiowoodley</a> <a href=\"http://t.co/y9LwLXeAZj\">pic.twitter.com/y9LwLXeAZj</a></p>&mdash; Sophie Pierce (@sophiepierce) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/sophiepierce/statuses/431332937750306817\">February 6, 2014</a></blockquote> </figure> <p>But this could only be the calm before another storm, as ITV's Jon Hill points out with the help of a grim looking forecast from the US Navy. <br></p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/JonHillITV/statuses/431202848299573248\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p><a href=\"https://twitter.com/search?q=%23ukstorm&amp;src=hash\">#ukstorm</a> This Saturday&#39;s stormy seas in the South West are forecast to much much bigger than today - US Navy <a href=\"http://t.co/cXmwFEkSQv\">pic.twitter.com/cXmwFEkSQv</a></p>&mdash; Jon Hill (@JonHillITV) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/JonHillITV/statuses/431202848299573248\">February 5, 2014</a></blockquote> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-52f33d6ce4b0530e249db05e\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-02-06T07:46:42.546Z\">7.46am <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><a href=\"http://youtu.be/84EQtsgA0_8\">Alarming YouTube footage</a> has emerged of the moment massive waves breached sea defences over Chesil beach, on the Dorset coast, at high tide on Wednesday.</p> <figure class=\"element element-video\" data-canonical-url=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=84EQtsgA0_8\"                                                                                > <iframe width=\"460\" height=\"259\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/84EQtsgA0_8?wmode=opaque&feature=oembed\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe> </figure> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-52f33941e4b0530e249db05d\" class=\"block is-summary\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2014-02-06T07:40:27.008Z\">7.40am <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">Summary</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Welcome to more live coverage of Britain's continuing flooding crisis as yet more storms are forecast. </p><p>Here's a summary of the latest developments:</p><p>• <a href=\"http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/public/weather/warnings/#?tab=warnings&amp;map=Warnings&amp;zoom=5&amp;lon=-3.50&amp;lat=55.50&amp;fcTime=1391644800&amp;regionName=uk\"><strong>The Met Office has warned that more heavy rain will sweep across southern Britain on Thursday and Friday, with a further deluge and very strong winds on Saturday.</strong></a> It still has an amber warning for rain across much of southern England, which warned the public to be prepared for \"disruption due to flooding\". A weather system developing off the Atlantic will sweep into <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2014/feb/06/two-turbulent-weather-system-batter-britain-weekend?CMP=twt_fd\">Britain bringing up to 1.4 ins (40mm) of rain overnight on Friday and into Saturday.</a></p><p>• <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2014/feb/05/storms-rain-uk-dawlish-floods\"><b>The latest storm left the far south-west of Britain isolated when the main rail line into the region buckled and broke. </b></a>Powerful waves smashed into homes on exposed stretches of the coast in Cornwall, Devon and Dorset with the seaside town of Dawlish bearing the brunt of the damage. <a href=\"http://www.networkrailmediacentre.co.uk/News-Releases/Engineers-working-to-restore-rail-services-in-Devon-and-Cornwall-1fc7.aspx\">Network Rail said a 80m stretch of the seawall has been damaged</a> prompting closure of the line \"until further notice\". <br></p><p>• <a href=\"http://www.environment-agency.gov.uk/homeandleisure/floods/31618.aspx\"><strong>The Environment Agency has reduced the number of severe flood warnings from nine to two, with a further 61 less serious flooding warnings in place.</strong></a> The two remaining severe warnings are on the stricken Somerset Levels where on Wednesday police used megaphone warnings from a helicopter to advice some residents to evacuate their homes. </p><p>• <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/feb/05/david-cameron-cobra-floods-help-south\"><strong>David Cameron took personal control of emergency efforts to help households stricken by floods on Wednesday and promised unrestricted help.</strong></a> The prime minister took over chairmanship of the government's disaster committee – Cobra – and pledged to do \"everything that can be done\" to help those affected and set aside an extra £100m to help with flood repairs and maintenance.</p> <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-69ca9ac0-51dd-4446-b552-85f943ee0bfc\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/2/6/1391672275953/9458d877-8b29-4985-aa62-7930af33e2ee-460x341.jpeg\" alt=\"Steve Bell on David Cameron's response to the flooding crisis\" width=\"460\" height=\"341\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>Steve Bell on David Cameron's response to the flooding crisis. Photograph: Copyright Steve Bell 2014/All Ri</figcaption> </figure> <p>• <a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-26057456\"><strong>The environment secretary, Owen Paterson, who has under pressure to get a grip of the flooding crisis, is being admitted to hospital for emergency surgery to repair a detached retina</strong>. </a> He is likely to be out of action for around a week and would not be giving a statement on Thursday to the Commons about the floods as planned.</p> </div> <p class=\"block-time updat