orning.</p><p>Bombardier missed out on the UK's last big train contract to build rolling stock for the upgrade to London's Thameslink network. The £1.6bn commission went to Germany's Siemens in 2011, prompting Bombardier to cut 1,200 jobs at its plant.</p><p>Following the uproar over the Thameslink contract, the government pledged to put British manufacturers on an \"equal footing\" with overseas competition but ministers remained constrained by European Union rules.</p><p>Andrew Wolstenholme, chief executive of Crossrail, said: \"Crossrail will transform rail services in London and the south-east. Procurement of the rolling stock and depot is just one more step in delivering this new railway and making it a reality for millions of passengers.</p><p>\"Crossrail Limited has conducted this procurement in a fair, objective and transparent manner and in full compliance with the regulatory framework.\"</p><p>If the contract had gone to a foreign bidder it would have been a severe embarrassment to the government and its efforts to encourage manufacturing. George Osborne declared a \"march of the makers\" in 2011 that was undermined by Siemens winning the Thameslink contract.</p><p>The £15bn Crossrail project will connect London's suburbs to the east and west, running through the centre of the city to increase rail capacity by 10%. London's already overcrowded transport system is set to face further demands as the population grows by an expected 1.6 million to 10 million over the next 15 years.</p><p>Bombardier has promised that at least 25% of the value of the contract will go to small and medium-sized enterprises (SMEs). Business secretary Vince Cable has consistently called for more support for SMEs, which make up more than half the UK economy.</p><p>TfL will start running the new trains from May 2017 on the existing rail network ahead of services starting on Crossrail's central section in December 2018.</p><p>Cable said: \"As well as providing a great boost to Bombardier and the Midlands this decision represents a real vote of confidence in British manufacturing. The government has been working hard with industry to support the UK rail supply chain to maximise growth opportunities through contracts like this. Our industrial strategy is giving business the confidence to invest – securing high-skilled jobs and a stronger economy.\"</p>","headline":"Bombardier UK wins £1bn Crossrail contract","trailText":"Derby-based train builder beats Japan's Hitachi and CAF of Spain to supply 65 trains for the line","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"theguardian.com","showInRelatedContent":"true","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/3mg3v","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Business/Pix/pictures/2014/2/6/1391674933087/Bombadier-factory-006.jpg","secureThumbnail":"https://static-secure.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Business/Pix/pictures/2014/2/6/1391674933087/Bombadier-factory-006.jpg","wordcount":"473","commentable":"true","internalContentCode":"429037808","allowUgc":"false","internalOctopusCode":"8652056","isPremoderated":"false","byline":"Sean Farrell","newspaperEditionDate":"2014-02-07T00:00:00Z","internalPageCode":"2039094","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-02-09T08:28:07Z"},"rights":{"syndicatable":true,"subscriptionDatabases":true},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2014/feb/06/bombardier-uk-crossrail-trains-contract-derby","apiUrl":"http://internal.content.guardianapis.com/business/2014/feb/06/bombardier-uk-crossrail-trains-contract-derby","tags":[{"id":"business/bombardier","webTitle":"Bombardier","type":"keyword","sectionId":"business","sectionName":"Business","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/business/bombardier","apiUrl":"http://internal.content.guardianapis.com/business/bombardier","references":[]},{"id":"business/manufacturing-sector","webTitle":"Manufacturing sector","type":"keyword","sectionId":"business","sectionName":"Business","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/busine