-political\" title=\"\">Michael Gove sacked the Ofsted chair Sally Morgan</a>, Laws told the Independent that her removal did not mark the education secretary's finest hour.</p><p>The minister rejected a peace offering from Gove, who said that the appointments panel to choose a successor could be chaired by the Lib Dem donor and education department non-executive director Paul Marshall.</p><p>Gove declined to deny speculation over the weekend that he intended to install the Tory donor and educationist Theodore Agnew as the new Ofsted chair. Laws said Gove should follow cabinet guidelines and allow Sir David Normington, the Public Appointments Commissioner, to appoint the panel chair.</p><p>In a move that will upset Gove and his allies, Laws called for an extension of the law to allow for inspector of academy \"chains\" – the non-profit making bodies that run academies. Ofsted can currently inspect individual academies. But it cannot inspect \"chains\" such as the School Partnership Trust Academies (SPTA) and the Elliot Foundation (TEF).</p><p>Tory sources say that Gove sacked Morgan because he wanted to put \"ideological backbone\" into the chief inspector of schools Sir Michael Wilshaw. Tories believe Wilshaw is following the orthodoxy of established inspectors and focusing harshly on new academies and free schools.</p><p>Laws told the Independent of his new plans for inspections of academy \"chains\", which will probably be included in the Lib Dem general election manifesto. He said: \"When the academies programme started, it had a lot of enemies and was regarded as a precious flower that needed protection. But this flower has now grown strong enough to survive in the full heat of the sun. There are some really good local authorities and there are still some terrible ones. In the same way, there are some good academy groups doing an absolutely fantastic job – like Ark and Harris – and some not doing so well.</p><p>\"Ofsted must be able to shine a spotlight wherever it wants to. I don't want there are to be any constraints. It ought to be able to inspect the chains.\"</p><p>Laws made clear his dismay at the removal of Morgan. He said: \"I don't think it is one of the best decisions that Michael Gove has ever made. I personally think that Sally Morgan has done a fantastic job as chair of Ofsted. I would rather she had remained and had her term renewed.\"</p>","headline":"Ofsted needs power to inspect groups that run academies, says David Laws","trailText":"Coalition rift emerges as education minister calls for extension of law to allow inspection of non-profit 'chains' that run schools","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"theguardian.com","showInRelatedContent":"true","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/3mg42","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/2/6/1391681939920/David-Laws-looks-at-the-c-004.jpg","secureThumbnail":"https://static-secure.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/2/6/1391681939920/David-Laws-looks-at-the-c-004.jpg","wordcount":"415","commentable":"true","internalContentCode":"429045498","allowUgc":"false","internalOctopusCode":"8652171","isPremoderated":"false","byline":"Nicholas Watt, chief political correspondent","newspaperEditionDate":"2014-02-07T00:00:00Z","internalPageCode":"2039123","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-02-09T10:32:15Z"},"rights":{"syndicatable":true,"subscriptionDatabases":true},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/feb/06/ofsted-powers-inspect-academies-groups-david-laws","apiUrl":"http://internal.content.guardianapis.com/politics/2014/feb/06/ofsted-powers-inspect-academies-groups-david-laws","tags":[{"id":"politics/education","webTitle":"Education policy","type":"keyword","sectionId":"politics","sectionName":"Politics","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/education","apiUrl":"http://internal.content.guardianapis.com/politics/education","references":[]},{"id":"politics/david-laws","