 Baillon was cleared by an internal investigation.</p><p>Following criticism of the sum he was awarded Baillon told BBC Radio Five Live on Thursday that he had not lost his temper when he struck the car window.</p><p>Baillon said he was on traffic patrol in a car when he noticed Robert Whatley, then aged 71, was not wearing a seat belt as he drove a Range Rover in south Wales in 2009.</p><p>Baillon said he pulled Whatley over, but he refused to give his name, was abusive, and then drove off. Baillon said he had feared the pensioner's car could drag him along the road.</p><p>A 17-minute pursuit followed through country roads, which was caught by a video camera inside the police car.</p><p>Whatley then pulled over and Baillon said he did not try to open the vehicle's door because its locking system may have made that impossible.</p><p>Instead, as seen in a video that went viral, he took a metal baton and repeatedly struck the side window of the pensioner's vehicle. He did so until it had smashed enough for the officer to get his arm in, grab the keys and immobilise the vehicle.</p><p>Baillon said he struck the side window of the pensioner's car no more than eight times, and was worried Whatley might have tried to drive off again and injure him or a colleague.</p><p>Baillon said when he had smashed the window and had control of the car, he said to Whatley: \"Calm down; it's over.\"</p><p>He said he then walked away, as shown in the video, to de-escalate the situation and let other colleagues deal with the pensioner.</p><p>Baillon said: \"I was completely in control of my actions.\"</p><p>He said he had used a \"conflict management\" model taught to officers, which saw him display an \"explosion of force\" to gain control. Baillon said a subsequent inquiry found his actions and adherence to his training was \"expertly\" carried out.</p><p>Baillon said: \"It wasn't temper, it was a strong use of force, that was required to get into the vehicle, to disable the vehicle, to stop it going any further.\"</p><p>Baillon said he accepted the video \"looks terrible in isolation\" but police work can sometimes look ugly: \"There are occasions when it looks terrible but its for the right reasons.\"</p><p>Baillon said despite internal investigations exonerating him, senior officers at Gwent police undermined him and failed to publicly back him.</p><p>He said the stress caused his wife to suffer a miscarriage and that at one point he even received a death threat.</p><p>Baillon said it was his force's failure to back him that left him feeling undermined, not jokes from colleagues about the clash with the pensioner, saying: \"It is not the case I threw my teddy out the pram because people were making jokes.\"</p><p>He added: \"I simply wanted them to acknowledge the impact it had on me and my family.\"</p><p>Baillon said when the video was leaked in 2011, it put great stress on him and his family.</p><p>He complained to his superiors but they did nothing to help him. Baillon claims that after his complaints he was moved from the traffic job he loved</p><p>\"After everything I had gone through, it was completely unfair for the organisation to move me,\" he said.</p><p>Baillon said the tribunal payments of £430,000 for the part of the pension he lost, plus £10,000 for lost wages, was fair.</p><p>Whatley received £20,000 from police for the damage to his car. He was fined by magistrates for motoring offences and ordered to pay £235 plus costs.</p><p>Gwent police have said they would reflect on the employment tribunal's judgment and award in Baillon's favour.</p>","headline":"Police officer who smashed pensioner's car window defends actions","trailText":"Former PC Mike Baillon makes comments after tribunal rules he was constructively dismissed in aftermath of incident","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"theguardian.com","showInRelatedContent":"true","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/3mg94","wordcount":"671","commentable":"false","internalContentCod